The '''Global Creativity Index''' (GCI) is a [[four dimensional]] ranking of countries. It combines individually-ranked countries based on [[creativity]], [[technology]], talent, and [[toleration|tolerance]] into an overall score. The top country in 2015 was Australia, followed by the United States, with New Zealand third.
The CGI is published by the [[Martin Prosperity Institute]], which belongs to the [[University of Toronto|University of Toronto's]] [[Rotman School of Management]].
<ref>{{cite web|url=https://idealog.co.nz/venture/2015/10/mike-hutcheson-why-we-shouldnt-celebrate-our-top-3-world-creativity-ranking|title=Mike Hutcheson: Why we shouldn't celebrate our top 3 world creativity ranking|date=23 October 2015|website=Idealog.co.nz|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://martinprosperity.org/content/the-global-creativity-index-2015/|title=The Global Creativity Index 2015 - Martin Prosperity Institute|website=Martinprosperity.org|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcinet.ca/en/2015/07/21/richard-floridas-global-creativity-index/|title=Richard Florida's Global Creativity Index|date=21 July 2015|website=Rcinet.ca|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/523124/these-are-the-worlds-most-creative-countries/|title=These are the world’s "most creative" countries|first=Jake|last=Flanagin|website=Qz.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/slovenia-ranks-16th-on-global-creativity-index|title=Slovenia ranks 16th on Global Creativity Index|website=Sloveniatimes.com|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>

