{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}} {{Infobox LGBT rights | location_header = Comoros {{flagicon|COM}} | image = LocationComoros.png | caption = [[Comoros]] | legal_status = Illegal<ref>{{cite web|title=State-Sponsored Homophobia|url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_SSHR_2014_Eng.pdf|website=International Lesbian Gay Bisexual Trans and Intersex Association|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> | penalty = 5 years imprisonment, fine<ref name="ILGA 2012">{{cite web|url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2012.pdf|title=State-sponsored Homophobia: A world survey of laws prohibiting same sex activity between consenting adults|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611181908/http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2012.pdf|archivedate=11 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> | gender_identity_expression = }}
'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT)''' persons in '''Comoros''' face legal challenges not experienced by non-[[LGBT]] residents. [[Comoros]] has laws applying to acts considered to be against nature. The age of consent is thirteen.
==Law regarding same-sexual activity== Both male and female sexual acts considered to be against nature are illegal in Comoros. Such acts are punished with up to five years imprisonment and a fine of 50,000 to 1,000,000 francs.<ref>{{cite web|title=State-Sponsored Homophobia|url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_SSHR_2014_Eng.pdf|website=International Lesbian Gay Bisexual Trans and Intersex Association|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref><ref name="Penal Code of the Federal Islamic Republic of Comoros">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.comores-droit.com/code/penal|title=Penal Code of the Federal Islamic Republic of Comoros|publisher=Comoros Law|date=|accessdate=4 March 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928105806/http://www.comores-droit.com/code/penal|archivedate=28 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Recognition of same-sex relationships== There is no recognition of legal rights for same-sex couples.
==Discrimination protections== There is no legal protection against [[discrimination]] based on [[sexual orientation]].
==Living conditions== The [[U.S. Department of State]]'s 2010 Human Rights Report found that "persons engaging in homosexual activity did not publicly discuss their sexual orientation due to societal pressure. There are no lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender organizations in the country."<ref>[https://www.state.gov/documents/organization/160116.pdf COMOROS]</ref>
