The '''Ministry of Healthcare of the Russian Federation'''<ref>[http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/putin-announces-cabinet-appointments/458907.html White House Announces Cabinet Members]</ref> ({{lang-ru|Министерство здравоохранения Российской Федерации}}, in short {{lang-ru|Минздрав России}} ''Minzdrav Rossii'') is an agency of the government of [[Russia]], headquartered in [[Moscow]].<ref>"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080520130333/http://www.minzdravsoc.ru/ministry/contacts/address Справочные телефоны, адрес и схема проезда]." Ministry of Healthcare and Social Development. Retrieved on 4 December 2010. "127994, ГСП-4, г. Москва, Рахмановский пер, д. 3"</ref> It is the successor of the former ''Ministry of Health and Social Development'', which was split in two in 2012 under Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev's First Cabinet|Dmitry Medvedev]], with the social security departments being relegated to the newly formed [[Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs (Russia)|Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs]]. Since then, [[Veronika Skvortsova]] has been the minister.

==Duties==
Its main official responsibilities include:
*developing and implementing state policy in healthcare;
*developing and implementing federal health programs, including initiatives on
diabetes, tuberculosis, health promotion, health education, disease prevention etc.;
*developing draft legislation and presenting it to the [[State Duma]];
*governance of federal medical facilities;
*medical education and manpower development;
*epidemiological and environmental health monitoring and health statistics;
*control of infectious diseases;
* development of health regulations;
* development of federal standards and recommendations for quality assurance;
* development and implementation of federal health programs 
*control and licensing of drugs.

