{{Distinguish|wikt:vigilant{{!}}vigilant}} {{Other uses}}
[[File:Fifes and Drums Vigilantes 1917 The Vigilantes.jpg|thumb|Publisher's design in ''Fifes and Drums Vigilantes'', 1917]]
'''The Vigilantes''' was a twentieth-century American publishing [[syndicate]]. Their pamphlets and newspapers were distributed with the intention of inspiring patriotism and [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] involvement in [[World War I]]. The membership was largely composed of men, who dominated its leadership, though much of the content was produced by women and appeared pseudonymously as the work of "the Vigilantes". A contemporary review noted the "breathless cries of song wrung mostly from the hearts of our women."<ref name="Wienen">{{cite book|last=Wienen|first=Mark W. Van |title=Partisans and poets: the political work of American poetry in the Great War|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1997|edition=2, illustrated|series=Cambridge studies in American literature and culture|pages=165|chapter=Marketing Patriotism|isbn=0-521-56396-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nIkCcLM5yQC&pg=PA165}}</ref>

The preface to a poetry anthology, published as Vigilantes Books: ''Fifes And Drums: A Collection of Poems of America at War'',<ref name="Wienen" /><ref>''[[s:Fifes and Drums|Fifes And Drums]]''. The Vigilantes. New York: George H. Doran. 1917.</ref> gave the following remarks on the authors' works:

<blockquote>These poems, written under the immediate stress of great events by those who have banded themselves together under the name of The Vigilantes, furnish a striking record of the emotional reactions of the American people during the fortnight preceding and the six weeks following the declaration of war....<ref>From the foreword of ''[[s:Fifes and Drums]]'' (1917).</ref></blockquote>

